<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTH BAY DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: HEARING ON PARKLAND AND STREET TAX 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Palos Verdes Estates City Council has set a public hearing on a proposed 
ballot measure to fund parklands and streets maintenance for Dec. 12 at 7:30 
p.m. 
</P>
<P>
The city is considering renewing the tax, which voters have approved by a 
two-thirds margin since 1980. If the council agrees to renew the parcel tax, it 
will be put on the April 10, 1990, city ballot. 
</P>
<P>
The last tax was approved for a four-year period in 1986, when voters agreed to 
pay $74 per parcel with a 4% increase per year. This year residents paid $84 
per parcel. 
</P>
<P>
Finance Director Bill Yeomans said he will probably propose at the public 
hearing that residents pay $88 or $89 per parcel with a 5% annual increase. 
</P>
<P>
The parcel tax pays 60% of the cost of maintaining streets and parklands, 
Yeomans said after the meeting, with the balance coming from the city's General 
Fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
