<P>
In an attempt to avoid state intervention, eight San Joaquin Valley counties 
have agreed to form a valleywide agency to control air pollution. Fresno County 
Supervisor Judy Andreen announced the agreement at a hearing before the state 
Senate Committee on Natural Resources and Wildlife. The hearing was called to 
consider a proposal by state Sen. Dan McCorquodale (D-San Jose) to require 
formation of a single air pollution control district in the San Joaquin Valley. 
Andreen said the new valleywide agency would replace individual air pollution 
control districts in Fresno, Kern, Kings, Madera, Merced, San Joaquin, 
Stanislaus and Tulare counties. Andreen said the agency is expected to be 
approved by the member counties by the end of the year. 
