<P>
CALIFORNIA IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
CROWLEY LAKE; 
</P>
<P>
PELICAN DEATHS TIED TO VARIETY OF CAUSES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
No single cause has been found in the deaths of 400 white pelicans at Crowley 
Lake in Mono County, the state Department of Fish and Game said. The pelican 
deaths, which happened over a two-week period in mid-October, may have been the 
result of changing environmental conditions elsewhere in the West, the 
department said. Starvation was the apparent primary cause of death in half the 
birds examined, but many also suffered intestinal infestations of parasitic 
worms severe enough to kill them. And some of the carcasses taken from the 
eastern Sierra lake contained high levels of mercury in the livers believed to 
be caused by increased exposure to an accumulation in the environment. 
</P>
