<HEADLINE>
<P>
TAPER, TOO ANNOUNCES 1990 SEASON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SYLVIE DRAKE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
New plays, a revival and a special engagement of the Taper's Improvisational 
Theatre Project (ITP) will constitute the 1990 season at the Mark Taper Forum's 
experimental Taper, Too. 
</P>
<P>
John Steppling's "The Thrill" (Jan.23-Feb.18), to be co-directed by the 
playwright and Taper associate artistic director Robert Egan, is described as 
"a story of tawdry love in a shopping mall with characters whose vulnerability 
and dreams are sometimes masked by emotional brutality." 
</P>
<P>
Beckett's "Waiting for Godot" will be revived by director Joseph Chaikin from 
March 6-April 1, while Tony Kushner's work-in-progress "Millenium Approaches," 
a play about Roy Cohn to be produced in association with San Francisco's Eureka 
Theatre (it was given a reading in the Taper's current Taper Lab '89 New Work 
Festival) will run May 8 to June 3. Oskar Eustis is the director. 
</P>
<P>
The ITP's "Robinson and Crusoe" by Nino D'Introna and Giacomo Ravicchio 
(translation by Shem Bitterman) will be staged by Peter C. Brosius April 10-21. 
This is a musical piece for children age eight and up that originated at 
Turin's Teatro Dell'Angolo and is being offered exclusively to Taper, Too 
subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
The Taper, Too is at 2580 Cahuenga Blvd. East (under the John Anson Ford 
Theatre) in Hollywood. Subscriptions are $36 for the three adult plays and an 
additional $4 (for kids) or $8 (for adults) for the ITP production (213) 
972-7373. SYLVIE DRAKE 
</P>
</TEXT>
