<LENGTH>
<P>
258 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
GORBACHEV SAYS HE WILL STEP UP PACE OF REFORM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ROME 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev said today that mistrust between East and 
West was crumbling before the pressure of democratic change. 
</P>
<P>
In a clear reference to reforms sweeping Eastern Europe, Gorbachev and Italian 
Prime Minister Giulio Andreotti called in a joint political declaration for 
democracy in every society. 
</P>
<P>
"In some countries an in-depth and courageous revision of both domestic and 
foreign policies is under way, and changes toward democracy are taking place," 
they said. 
</P>
<P>
"Under the pressure of these factors, the curtain of mistrust between the East 
and the West is crumbling," the declaration added. 
</P>
<P>
It was signed after talks between the two leaders on the second day of 
Gorbachev's visit to Italy. 
</P>
<P>
Earlier, as he entered the talks in the renaissance Villa Madama overlooking 
Rome, Gorbachev told reporters his reform of Soviet society was facing great 
difficulties and he appealed for more cooperation from the West so military 
expenditure could be cut. 
</P>
<P>
But he said he would step up the pace of reform. 
</P>
<P>
He said: "Now we are going through the most difficult phase because we have 
entered a period which I would call one of profound transformation. Not 
everything is going easily and there are difficulties, but there are no roads 
for turning back. 
</P>
<P>
"We are going to forge ahead and step up the pace of reforms." 
</P>
<P>
He said through an interpreter he wanted to improve the quality of Soviet life. 
"In order to achieve this, we would like to see more favorable external 
conditions to enable us to reduce military expenditure." 
</P>
</TEXT>
