<P>
HOUSTON SET TO BE SITE OF ECONOMIC SUMMIT IN 1990 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Bush has selected Houston as the site of the next economic summit for 
the seven major Western industrial countries, White House sources said today. 
</P>
<P>
They said the summit, with the United States as host, will take place next 
July. 
</P>
<P>
"It is expected to be announced tomorrow," said one White House official, when 
Bush will be in Malta for his first summit with Soviet leader Mikhail S. 
Gorbachev. 
</P>
<P>
The Houston Chronicle reported today that the summit would take place July 7 to 
9. 
</P>
<P>
Bush indicated during last July's economic summit in Paris that he would like 
to see Texas be host to the gathering of industrial nations, even though it can 
have sweltering heat at that time of year. 
</P>
<P>
Bush, a native of Connecticut, moved to Houston after World War II and made his 
fortune in the oil business. 
</P>
<P>
The summit, which rotates among the participating nations, was last hosted by 
the United States in 1983 in Williamsburg, Va. 
</P>
