<P>
THE SIDELINES; 
</P>
<P>
YANKEES SIGN HALL: $3.3 MILLION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mel Hall, acquired by the Yankees from Cleveland last spring, stayed with New 
York when he agreed today to a three-year contract for a guaranteed $3.3 
million. 
</P>
<P>
Hall, a 29-year-old outfielder, gets a $300,000 signing bonus and salaries of 
$1 million in 1990, 1991 and 1992. He can earn about $250,000 each year in 
performance bonuses. 
</P>
<P>
He batted .260 last season with 17 home runs and 58 RBIs. The Yankees were 15-1 
in games in which he homered. 
</P>
<P>
Hall has a .278 career batting average with 88 homers and 408 RBIs in 
seven-plus seasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
