<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE SIDELINES; 
</P>
<P>
AUSSIES COURT CHANG, SANCHEZ 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MELBOURNE, Australia 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Michael Chang and Arantxa Sanchez are the two remaining names on the shopping 
list of the Australian Open tennis championship. 
</P>
<P>
Chang, the French Open champion, has said he will take a break from tennis 
early in 1990 and plans to miss the first Grand Slam tournament of the decade; 
Sanchez also plans a vacation. 
</P>
<P>
Tennis Australia President Geoff Pollard said Wednesday that he would make a 
new approach to Chang, ranked fifth in the world, in an attempt to change his 
mind before entries for the Jan. 15-28 championships close on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
Sanchez, the French Open women's champion, will contest the Hopman Cup mixed 
teams event in Perth from Dec. 26 to Jan. 1 but is then scheduled to return 
home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
